The Influence of the Internet on the World (With a focus on Singapore)

The Invention of the Internet and its subsequent commercialization has been influencing every part of our lives.
From https://www.brookings.edu/research/the-economy-and-the-internet-what-lies-ahead/#:~:text=The%20Internet%20will%20produce%20significant,faster%20growth%20in%20living%20standards.:
The Internet will produce significant cost savings in many sectors of the economy, resulting in faster productivity growth. It will also produce lower prices for consumers, resulting in faster growth in living standards.

The Internet should also generate a variety of benefits to users, in their capacities as consumers and citizens, that are not easily quantified but nonetheless real: savings in time, added convenience, and products and services tailored specifically to them. In an era when consumers are aware more than ever that “time is money, these benefits to many may be more noticeable and appreciated than the numbers that economists like to count.

This study will go into how the rise of Internet and some various sub-breakthroughs affects Nations and their population such as
-Is there a trend between having a high GDP and high internet usage?
-When exactly did the internet go 'mainstream' in 1st World Countries?
-When did the internet go 'mainstream' in Most Developed Countries/First world countries?
-How does high HDI correlate high internet speed and does is there a big difference between high and low HDI?
-Which age group uses more internet and when was the period with the most internet usage growth.
-What type of broadband connection became the most dominant at what time and why?
-How has the Internet changed the Singaporean Economy specifically the Info-Comm Industry.
-How has the rise of the internet affected the amount of mobile phones, and what might be the reason why?
-What do Singaporeans do with their mobile phones, how has that changed over the years and what generation uses mobile phones the most.
This study's focus is on 1980 onwards as the internet before then was not meant for consumers.

It will focus specifically on Singapore.

The Rise of the internet as a daily part of our lives began around the 1990s. Its rise along with mobile phones allowed us to communicate with anyone, anywhere at any time.
Hypothetically, the internet would provide an immense advantage to the nation's businesses and productivity, specifically the GDP per Capita, due to having instant communication to do trade with others as well as increasing productivity. Using a Scatterplot graph, I will try and answer the question,
Is there a trend between having a high GDP and high internet usage?

I will highlight Prominent Nations and Singapore to provide a bench mark.


The Datasets below contain the total GDP per capita of all the countries in the world (Including some areas that are grouped together, however, those are dropped from the data.) and the percentage of people using internet in the world. Both datasets include different years starting from 1960 to the present day. However, we will be focusing on 2017.

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#These are not countries, so i will drop them to not affect our data.
worldDatabank_Drop_Rows = ["World","High income","OECD members","Post-demographic dividend","IDA & IBRD total","Low & middle income","Middle income","IBRD only","East Asia & Pacific","Upper middle income","Europe & Central Asia","North America","Late-demographic dividend","East Asia & Pacific (excluding high income)","East Asia & Pacific (IDA & IBRD countries)","European Union","Euro area","Early-demographic dividend","Lower middle income","Latin America & Caribbean","Latin America & the Caribbean (IDA & IBRD countries)","Latin America & Caribbean (excluding high income)","Europe & Central Asia (IDA & IBRD countries)","South Asia","South Asia (IDA & IBRD)","Middle East & North Africa","Europe & Central Asia (excluding high income)","Arab World","IDA total","Sub-Saharan Africa","Sub-Saharan Africa (IDA & IBRD countries)","Sub-Saharan Africa (excluding high income)","Korea, Rep.","Fragile and conflict affected situations","Central Europe and the Baltics","Middle East & North Africa (excluding high income)","Middle East & North Africa (IDA & IBRD countries)","Pre-demographic dividend","IDA only","Heavily indebted poor countries (HIPC)","Low income","Other small states","Small states","Caribbean small states","Pacific island small states"]
focusCountries = ['China','United States','Japan','Singapore','Denmark','Netherlands','France','India']

#Reading data
#The skiprows and header parameters are due to the header and other useless information present in the .csv file.
df_total_gdp_per_capita = pd.read_csv('total_GDP_per_capita.csv',skiprows=[1,2],header=1).set_index("Country Name").drop(worldDatabank_Drop_Rows)
df_global_internet = pd.read_csv('internet_usage_global.csv',error_bad_lines=False).set_index("Country Name")

#Cleaning the data, then sorting it to get only 2017s data
#Here i drop the 2 columns that are not needed and the countries above, then i get only 2017s data
df_global_internet_sort = df_global_internet.drop(columns=["Indicator Name","Indicator Code"]).drop(worldDatabank_Drop_Rows).loc[:,'2017']
df_total_gdp_per_capita_sort = df_total_gdp_per_capita.drop(columns=["Indicator Name","Indicator Code"]).loc[:,'2017']

#Setting
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.grid() 
plt.xlabel("GDP Per Capita")
plt.ylabel("Percentage of population having access to Internet in 2017")
plt.title("Internet Usage in Percentage over GDP per capita in 2017")

#This sets a new coloumn and with the default values
df_total_gdp_per_capita['color'] = 'Black'
df_total_gdp_per_capita['size'] = 20
df_total_gdp_per_capita['label'] = None

#These following statements only select those focus i want to focus on.
#This makes sure only the important countries are labelled.
df_total_gdp_per_capita.loc[df_total_gdp_per_capita.index.isin(focusCountries),'label'] = df_total_gdp_per_capita[df_total_gdp_per_capita.index.isin(focusCountries)].index

#This only colors the important countries
df_total_gdp_per_capita.loc[df_total_gdp_per_capita.index.isin(focusCountries),'color'] = ["Yellow","Orange","Red","Grey","Green","Pink","Purple","Blue"]

#This makes the important countries bigger
df_total_gdp_per_capita.loc[df_total_gdp_per_capita.index.isin(focusCountries),'size'] = 80

for label in np.arange(0,df_total_gdp_per_capita_sort.to_numpy().size,1):
    #The color takes from the Color Column
    #The label takes from the Label Column, if default there is no label
    #The size takes from the size column.
    plt.scatter(df_total_gdp_per_capita_sort[label],df_global_internet_sort[label],label=df_total_gdp_per_capita.loc[:,'label'][label],c=df_total_gdp_per_capita.loc[:,'color'][label],s=df_total_gdp_per_capita.loc[:,'size'][label])

plt.legend()
plt.show()

As we can see here, there is an obvious increasing Trend between high GDP Per Capita and a high percentage of the population having access to the internet.

Most countries in this spectrum have at least >80% of the population having access to the internet
This means that countries which have good internet infrastructure are overall more efficent and productive(such as Singapore and Japan)as they have higher GDP per capita's than other countries without high Internet Access.

df_internet = pd.read_csv('share-of-individuals-using-the-internet.csv').set_index('Year')

#These are countries i want to focus on
focus_countries = np.array(['Singapore','Japan','United States','Australia','South Korea'])

plt.xlabel("Years")
plt.ylabel("Percentage of the Population Using the Internet")
plt.grid()

#Plotting
for x in focus_countries:
    plt.plot(df_internet[df_internet.loc[:,"Entity"] == x]["Individuals using the Internet (% of population) (% of population)"],label=x)

plt.legend()
plt.show()

The countries focused in the graph all start having a small percentage using the internet in 1992-1997.
After that, it has an upward trend which peaks in 2000, At this point, they are hovering around the 40%-55% mark.
After 2000, there is a large upward trend where each nation's percentages improve massively ending in most nations having their percentages around 75%-95% in 2017.
This data does not take into account how fast the internet was. The nation's could count Dial-up internet or Other forms of internet which is very slow and outdated by today's standards. However, we can still see that the internet first came to market in most developed nations at around 1993-1995 but it wasnt until 2000 that the internet was popular and started getting more traction.

In conclusion, the internet went 'mainstream' in 2000 in most countries.

The more developed a country is(measured in HDI), the more money they can spend on infrastructure that can support higher internet speed as it is common sense.
But how big is the difference, and does high HDI really mean high internet speed?
 I split countries into 4 groups based on this ranking:
http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/2019-human-development-index-ranking .
-Highly Developed -> Top 20 on the HDI
-Mildy Developed -> 20-40
-Developed -> 60-80
-Developing -> Last 20
Then I used a boxplot to show the difference.

In [568]:
df_internet_speed = pd.read_csv('internet_speed.csv').set_index('country').drop(columns="pop2020")


Highly_Developed_arr = np.array(['Norway','Switzerland','Ireland','Germany','Hong Kong','Australia','Iceland','Sweden','Singapore','Netherlands','Denmark','Finland','Canada','New Zealand','United Kingdom','United States','Belgium','Liechtenstein','Japan','Austria','Luxembourg'])#top 20
Mildy_Developed_arr = np.array(['Portugal','Qatar','Chile','Brunei','Hungary','Bahrain','Croatia','Oman','Argentina','Russia','Belarus','Kazakhstan','Bulgaria','Montenegro','Romania','Barbados','Kuwait','Uruguay','Turkey','Bahamas','Latvia'])#top40-60
Developed_arr = np.array(['Malaysia','Seychelles','Serbia','Trinidad and Tobago','Iran','Mauritius','Panama','Costa Rica','Albania','Georgia','Sri Lanka','Cuba','Saint Kitts and Nevis','Antigua and Barbuda','Bosnia and Herzegovina','Mexico','Thailand','Grenada','Brazil','Colombia'])#60-80
Developing_arr = np.array(['Afghanistan','Djibouti','Malawi','Ethiopia','Gambia','Haiti','Liberia','Yemen','Senegal','DR Congo','Mozambique','Sierra Leone','Burkina Faso','Benin','Mali','Burundi','Sudan','Madagascar','Mauritania','Niger'])#last 20

#Creating Sorting Information
Highly_Developed_internet = df_internet_speed[df_internet_speed.index.isin(Highly_Developed_arr)]['broadbandSpeed']

Mildy_Developed_internet = df_internet_speed[df_internet_speed.index.isin(Mildy_Developed_arr)]['broadbandSpeed']
    
Developed_internet = df_internet_speed[df_internet_speed.index.isin(Developed_arr)]['broadbandSpeed']
    
Developing_internet = df_internet_speed[df_internet_speed.index.isin(Developing_arr)]['broadbandSpeed']

#Stacking them together
totalArr = (np.vstack([Highly_Developed_internet,Mildy_Developed_internet,Developed_internet,Developing_internet]))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.title("Network Speed in Mbps in 2019")
plt.ylabel("Speed in Mbps")
plt.yticks(np.arange(0,250,50))
plt.ylim(0)

plt.boxplot(totalArr.T,widths=0.2,labels=["Highly Developed Countries","Mildly Developed Countries","Developed Countries","Developing Countries"])
plt.grid()
plt.show()

From the graph, we can see that, obviously, Highly Developed Countries outclasses all the other groups. But it seems some countries in the Highly Developed Countries are still below 50 Mbps.
The Mildy Developed Countries and Developed Countries are still close in terms of speed.
It also seems that Developing countries have abyssmal internet speeds when compared to the Highly Developed Countries.
This may be due to the fact that the Countries with more development have more money to support infrastructure for higher internet speeds when there is a breakthrough in internet speeds.
Countries with less development cannot afford to spend money on internet infrastructure when their priority is, for example, Healthcare.

In Conclusion, there is a trend between HDI and internet speed, however, it is not a absolute factor as some of the developed countries have faster internet speeds than the Mildly Developed Countries.
The difference between Highly Developed and developing is big in terms of internet speeds, however, while there is an obvious trend, it should not be assumed that if a country is developing or has low HDI, it has low internet speeds as some countries defy this trend and have internet speed that does not fit the trend.

df_IndividualInternetUsage = pd.read_csv('individual-internet-usage-by-age.csv').set_index('year')

#Replacing all of the 50-59 and 60 and above to "50 and above" to be .groupby'ed later.
df_IndividualInternetUsage_replaced = df_IndividualInternetUsage.replace(["50 to 59 years","60 and above"],"50 and above")

#I first reset_index to get the year,which is the index.
#I then Group the "50 and above" that was changed earlier, into 1 row and get the mean.
#I also group'd by year and set Sort to false to preserve the order. I then re set the year.
df_IndividualInternetUsage_reformat = df_IndividualInternetUsage_replaced.reset_index().groupby(by=["age","year"],sort=False).mean().reset_index().set_index('year')

#Plotting, I plotted by each age group.
for x in df_IndividualInternetUsage_reformat.groupby(by='age',sort=False).sum().index:
    plt.plot(df_IndividualInternetUsage_reformat[df_IndividualInternetUsage_reformat.iloc[:,0] == x].loc[:,"internet_usage"],label=x)

plt.legend()
plt.grid()
plt.title("Percentage of Singaporeans who used internet before by age group")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Percentage who used internet before")
plt.show()

From the first graph, we can see that the proportion of Singaporeans that have used internet before skyrockets from 2000-2004 going from below 40% to around 60%.
There is some stagnation,decreases and slight increases from here to 2012. However, from 2013 onwards, there is a large increase in the amount of people using the internet. This could be due to the intorudction of smart nation in 2014, and in 2017 when the government dedicated 2.4 Billion to this initiative.

The second graph had some issues as in 2014, the format changed from having 50 and above being 1 category to having 50-60 and 60 and above. My solution to this formatting issue was to rename the 2 new columns into a 50 and above column, use .groupby to group all of them together and sum them into 1 row. This formatting still gives the correct data. There is an issue with the data where all the 2011 and 2013 data seems very abnormal, showing unexpected spikes in usage. However, I have no replacement data so I cannot fix this problem.

In the second graph, we can see that majority of the people have used internet before are those that are 34 years and less of age. Those who are 35 and above are consistently lower than their peers in 2007, however, after 2007, the 35-49 age group increases to where the only outlier is the 50 and above group. This may be due to the fact that they are forced to learn about and use the internet in order to be useful in the workforce or simply as it is a new technology that everybody else is using. A commonality in all of the years is that the 50 and above are below the rest. This has started to change however, in 2017 there was a large increase from the past year and 2018 has the same trend. This could be due to the fact that they realize that technology is overtaking old-fashioned methods and want to adapt.

In conclusion, in most of the years, the 7-34 year olds have used internet the most, along with 35-49 year olds past 2016. The period with the most internet growth is 2000-2004, a close second would be 2013-2018.

We should also look at what kind of broadband connection most users have at the time. It represents how fast their internet speeds can possibly be. A fibre internet connection can reach up to 2 Gbps while a wired internet is usually around 96 Mbps. A fast internet connection allows more data be streamed or sent to the internet. A question we can answer here is,
What type of broadband connection became the most dominant at what time and why?

So from this graph, we can see that in 2008 Fixed broadband is the dominant segment in the industry with a small amount of Wireless broadband.

In 2012, Fixed broadband was still in the majority, with Fibre and Wireless holding around 25% each. The small amount of Fibre could be that it is a new technology at this point as it was introduced to Singapore in September 2010.
Source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_in_Singapore

In 2016, Fibre is now in the majority holding around 70%. This is probably due to the fact that Fibre is faster, has less latency, and is probably the best option among the 3. However, Fibre takes a long time to install compared to Wired.(1-2 Weeks compared to 3-5 Days)This could be the reason why fibre has not completely made Fixed broadband obselete.

In 2018, Fibre holds around 80-90% of all connections. Wireless and Fixed broadband have around 10% each. The reasons they are not completely gotten rid of may be because the users did not need the extra speed, or cannot afford the upgrade. Wireless broadband is also useful as it allows the user mobility that Fibre and Fixed broadband cannot have.

In conclusion, Fibre is now the dominant Connection type in Singapore, overtaking fixed broadband around 2012-2016 due to its advantages of being faster. Before 2016, the majority would be fixed broadband. This means Majority of Singaporeans have access to 1gbps or more internet speeds as fiber supports 1gbps+ connections.

df_uni = pd.read_csv('universities-intake-enrolment-and-graduates-by-course.csv').set_index('year')

#Get all Information Technology students, group them by year and sum them together to add the genders together, then drop the useless columns.

#Use this to get rid of the "," when the number is too high.
df_uni_reformat = df_uni_group.replace({',':''}, regex=True)

From the graph, we can see that Enrolment is around the same as Intake and Graduates in 2005-2007. However in 2008, the number of enrolment sky rockets to nearly 11 times its value in the previous year. Besides decreasing slightly in 2010, the enrolment amount keeps on increasing at a steady pace from 2011 to reach 61 Million. The Graduate and Intake numbers remain the same until 2018 where there is a slight increase. However, this increase is overshadowed by the very large increases in Enrolment.

There could be some reasons why even though enrolment is increasing, the Intake or Graduates are not. This could be due to the Singaporean government keeping standards high for graduates:https://international.thenewslens.com/article/68084, or some other reasons.

The large increase in enrolment could be attributed to the increasing popularity of Information Technology as a job. Most of the people probably applying grew up with the internet and thus want to pursue a higher education in something they enjoy. To conclude this graph,The rise of the internet has helped to increase the amount of skilled labour able to work in the Singaporean infocomm industry.

The first graph(The bar graph) is a representation of the total revenue split by its exports and imports by every year. From this graph, we can see that from 2001, the total revenue increased from 30 Billion to 200 Billion.
In terms of comparing Domestic and Export revenues, the Domestic revenue has increased from 20 Billion in 2001 to around 140 Billion in 2017 whereas Export revenue grew from 10 Billion to 60 Billion.
In conclusion, there has been more domestic growth than Export revenue throughout the years.

The second graph is a line graph depicting most of the market-segments throughout the years. From this graph, we can see that the Hardware revenue accounts for most of our revenue. We can also see the rise of Hardware dominating the total revenue starting in 2008 to 2017. We also see that the rest of the market-segments are stagnant, they did not change a lot when compared to the changes in Hardware.

The 2 graphs show that the infocomm industry is growing especially the domestic segment along with the hardware segment.

As for the pie charts,they are meant to compare how much they emphasize how prominent the hardware market-segment is, even in 2001. In 2001, it accounted for around 40% of the total revenue. While in 2017, it accounts for 75% of the total revenue. It also shows the decline of the content services . In 2001, it was a small chunk of the revenue, while 2017 it has no reported revenue.

import matplotlib.patches as mpatches

def pie_age(x,unique_val):
    return pd.unique(df_devices_rename[df_devices_rename.index.isin([x])].loc[:,unique_val])
def pie_seg(x):
    return df_devices_rename[df_devices_rename.index.isin([x])].groupby(by=["media_activity",'age','year','sample_size']).mean().sort_values(["age","media_activity"])

df_devices = pd.read_csv("usage-of-mobile-devices-for-media-activities.csv").set_index('year')
coloring = ["#AFAFAF","#8C8C8C","#8C8C8C","#464646","#212121","000000"]
coloring_act = ['#00D97D','#ACC900','#B90043','#220DAA','#1D9A6C','#4B6BA2',"#39ff14"]

#Rename certain acitivities to make the graph less cluttered later
df_devices_rename = df_devices.replace(["Watch MediaCorp TV","Watch Singtel TV","Watch StarHub TV"], "Watch TV").replace(["Access non-media-related apps and websites","Access media-related apps and websites"],"Access apps and websites").replace(['Watch videos','Watch movies','Watch animation'],"Watch Media").replace(['Listen to music','Listen to the radio'],"Listen to Media").replace(['Read books','Read magazines'],"Read Media")

df_devices_rename['total'] = df_devices_rename['sample_size']*(df_devices_rename['ever_used']/100)

df_devices_rename['difference'] = df_devices_rename['sample_size'] - df_devices_rename['total']

#Iterates through years.
for y in np.unique(df_devices.index):
    df_devices_rename_segments = pie_seg(y)[['total','difference']].to_numpy().flatten()
    
    #Plotting
    plt.pie(pie_age(y,"sample_size"),radius=1.2,wedgeprops=dict(width=0.3, edgecolor='w'),colors=coloring,labels=pie_age(y,"age"))
   
    #Plots for each section
    y1 = 0
    
    for x in enumerate(coloring_act):
        plt.pie(df_devices_rename_segments[[y1,y1+1,y1+14,y1+15,y1+28,y1+29,y1+42,y1+43,y1+56,y1+57,y1+70,y1+71]],radius=1.1-y1/20,wedgeprops=dict(width=0.3, edgecolor='w'),colors=[x[1],'white'])
        y1 += 2
    
    #This handles the middle circle
    centre_circle = plt.Circle((0,0),0.4,color='black', fc='white',linewidth=0)
    plt.title(y)
    fig = plt.gcf()
    fig.set_size_inches(12,12) 
    fig.gca().add_artist(centre_circle)
    
    #Add custom Legend, Manually Add the legend so as to not clutter it.
    plt.legend()
    handles, labels = plt.gca().get_legend_handles_labels()
    
    #This changes the Legend to be something more clean
    for i in enumerate(coloring_act):
        handles.append(mpatches.Patch(color=i[1], label=df_devices_rename.groupby(by='media_activity').sum().index[i[0]]))

    plt.legend(handles=handles,loc='center')
    plt.show()

From the graph, we can see that the main thing is that people of all age groups most of the time use Mobile phones to access applications and websites. It accounts for most of the usage of mobile phones. A second would be Accessing news or Listening to Media. However, the segment "Access apps and websites" is very ambigious.

A interesting difference between years is that the 60-65,50-59 age groups both have reported increased use of the mobile device to Access apps and websites segments in 2015 compared to 2013. This could be due to them being educated by their peers on how to utilize their devices to their full potential.

There is also differences between ages. In 2013, the 60-65 age group has little to no "Play Video Games" segment and a relatively large amount of "Access news" Segment compared to the 15-19 age group which has a relatively large "Play Video Games" segment and smaller "Watch TV" Segment. This could be due to the fact that most 60-65 year olds do not play video games and rely on old methods such as newspapers or the Television where it is different in the 15-19 year old age group.

In conclusion, This graph tells me that as time goes on, more people use mobile phones for apps and websites than other functions. Although the segment "Access apps and websites" is very ambiguous and could mean anything, it is constantly the largest part of the graph.

The graphs also finds that the from 2013-2015, more people access apps and websites compared from 2013 to 2015.For example, only a small amount of 50-59 aged people used their phone for apps and websites while in 2015, there was a significantly large amount that used their phone for apps and websites.

This graph also finds that most of the people who uses mobile phones are between 15-49, however, an increasingly large part of the population that is above 50 also accounts for phone usage from 2013 onwards.

To summarize the study up, The internet has provided countries a way to increase their productivity and their GDP per capita. This is supported by a scatterplot where a trend was found in where high GDP per capita countries are also the ones with high internet access.

The Internet likely first became available in developed countries in 1993-1995, but didnt gain mainstream popularity until 2000. For example, internet access didnt become 50% in USA until 2001 and 75% in 2007. Internet speeds can also be used to determine how developed a country is, however, it is only true up to a certain extent. For example, while it is true that a country that is very low on the Human Developmental Index has a slower internet speed than one that is very High, it will be hard to tell,for example, a rank 12 country and a rank 50 country apart. This is because as shown in the boxplot, highly and mildly developed countries occupy around the same range on the graph.

Singapore has been pushing to become a smart nation suggested by the Smart Nation Intiative was launched in 2014. Singapore has 85% of its population having access to the internet from 35% in 2000. Because of this change and/or other factors, its elder generations(35-60) have greater accessibility to the internet and its uses, its infocomm job market doubled in size from around 110k in 2002 to 225k in 2017 and its enrolment has increased dramatically from under 10 Million being enrolled in 2005 to over 60 Million in 2018, its intake has also increased slightly. This was also the case in the Mobile Phone Dataset as we see more people use their smartphone for apps and websites instead of just calling and communication. From most of the graphs and their conclusions, we can say that the Smart Nation Intiative was a sucess as its purpose was to help educate and make Singaporeans more tech-savvy.

A closer look into its infocomm industry reveals that the industry grew from 30 Billion in 2001 to 200 Billion. Most of the Infocomm industry is based on domestic revenue and the largest market segment and the most grown is hardware where it grew from 20 Billion to 150 Billion. This means that it occupied 75% of the infocomm market in 2017. The graphs also revealed that content services are not a part of the market anymore since 2017.

A related sub-development are mobile phones, mobile phone subscriptions went from 0.5 Million to 8 Million at the end of 2018. Most people who use mobile phones are between 15-40 years of age, however this is changing.
